{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17246"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.75,0.13,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9936"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10777"},{"type":"tags","id":"11066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer development involves the accumulation of genetic changes over time. These changes can affect different types of genes and have varying impacts on cell growth and survival.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes somatic mutations in cancer development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arise exclusively in tumour suppressor genes","Accumulate randomly in multiple genes over time","Develop only within rapidly proliferating tissues","Transfer directly from parent to offspring","Exist in all body cells from conception"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer develops through the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccumulation of random mutations in multiple genes over time\u003C/strong\u003E. These mutations can affect both proto-oncogenes (which promote cell growth) and tumour suppressor genes (which inhibit cell growth).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise exclusively in tumour suppressor genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Somatic mutations occur in multiple gene types, including both proto-oncogenes and tumour suppressor genes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelop only within rapidly proliferating tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - Mutations can occur in any cell type, regardless of proliferation rate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer directly from parent to offspring\u003C/strong\u003E - Somatic mutations occur after conception and are not inherited\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExist in all body cells from conception\u003C/strong\u003E - These would be germline mutations, not somatic mutations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome mutations (drivers) provide selective growth advantage to cells, while others (passengers) occur randomly but do not contribute to cancer development. The accumulation of driver mutations leads to progressive loss of growth control and eventual cancer formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Somatic mutations occur in body cells after conception and are not inherited by offspring.","Cancer typically requires multiple somatic mutations affecting both proto-oncogenes and tumour suppressor genes.","Driver mutations provide selective growth advantage while passenger mutations do not contribute to cancer development."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:28:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:31:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9936"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4937"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97\ufe0f","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T2